data.title: R U Kidding
data.text: Best breakfast ever! Bone marrow? Egg en croute or lamb sausage for brunch and or breakfast beside a typical egg Benedict make the right way?

data.title: Delicious light French cuisine
data.text: Quick service, delicious food, great for a light lunch.. The fig, prosciutto, and brie sandwich is particularly delicious

data.title: French treats!
data.text: From coffee to pastries to tartines this place is amazing. It can be a bit expensive for a student budget but it is worth every penny and a real treat to visit.

data.title: A true Pastry Heaven
data.text: The desserts rotate daily so that there are new and amazing sweets to try each and every day.  Killer brownies, fruit pastry turn-overs, stunning cakes and cookies, bread puddings, chocolates, truffles, and etc, etc, etc (and coffee!!!).  Each day is a new delight. (a full restaurant fare as well). This is without a doubt the best pastry and sweets resource in NW Arkansas.

data.title: Put this on your bucket list
data.text: Delicious, fresh, nice presentation. Everything looks yummy. We found this place while walking through the farmers market. Met two of the three chef-owners. We might return tomorrow for breakfast.

data.title: French bistro by a French trained artist
data.text: Go. Eat. Enjoy an espresso. You'll be delighted and surprised! Quiche, salads, sweets, breads. A local favorite.

data.title: Coffee Junkies will be happy!
data.text: Awesome French Press coffee and the French toast was next level good. Pastries are wonderful. My husband I went for a Sunday morning brunch. Absolutely charming environment. The restaurant is small, but that just adds to it. Will return on our next Fayetteville trip. WPS!

data.title: Wonderful pastries and more
data.text: Delightful people, wonderful pastries and delicious entres is what makes Bouchee a great place in Fayetteville.  We are fortunate to have this little jewel in our city.  I have never had a bad thing here.  You can count on them to make it wonderful.

data.title: Breakfast
data.text: What a great place to visit!! The food and service were both amazing!! We will definitely be returning on our next visit!!

data.title: Fabulous French Bistro!
data.text:
This quaint little bistro is located right on the square in Fayetteville, so it's easy access to everything, including The Chancellor Hotel where we stayed. (right across the street). 

I had the Meurette Oeufs Benedict, my husband had the Lardon & Chive Omelette and our friend had the fruit salad. All were simply divine. They were also serving crepes and french toast, and everything we saw looked amazing. We only wish that we were going to be there for lunch because their lunch menu looked fabulous as well. Just go to their FB website and scroll through the food porn! It'll make you want to dine there as well. 

When we go back to Fayetteville, we are DEFINITELY going back.

data.title: Everything is great!
data.text: I haven't had anything yet I didn't like! I love to meet my clients here for lunch. I love the grilled Gruyere sandwich and the macaroons are amazing!

data.title: Tasty pastry and such
data.text: Really enjoyed our sandwiches from here. Tried the  prosciutto, brie, and fig tartine, and the gruyere/onion/mustard one. They were both tasty. Portions might have been a bit small for our appetites. Brownie was amazing! And huge! Will be back to try more menu items. Really excited that Fayetteville has a restaurant serving bone marrow and some classic french dishes. Can't believe we didn't try it sooner but I guess it is sort of tucked away.

data.title: Hidden Gem of Fayetteville
data.text: Excellent pastries!  Very relaxing casual ambiance and truly a delight to visit.  Service was impeccable, staff friendly, and food delicious.  What else can you ask for?

data.title: Eating at the square
data.text: As authentic french food as I have found in the U.S.  Very impressive selection that is well prepared. Comparable to food I have eaten in France. Pleasant. Small. Clean and bright with gracious staff. Open day hours, not for dinner.

data.title: WOW
data.text:
The beautiful space Bouchee occupies has been one of those restaurant spots that has repeatedly failed for the saddest reasons. Bouchee, however, is turning a profit with the delicacies and atmosphere. Very Frenchy croissants—slightly crisp on the outside and lightly dough-chewy on the inside. BIG suckers. Sam makes every cup of French-pressed coffee to order (they call it 'handcrafted' coffee). WOW. The variety of pastries is infinite and includes scones, sandwich cookies, sticky buns with almond slivers, custards. Go to their Web site and take a look at the 100s of offerings in this category alone. 

Then there is homemade soup and sandwiches like paper thin prosciutto on a baguette with delightful tangy sauce. Salads and fresh sea bass are blasts of creativity and, like everything else that comes from the kitchen, simple as pie but with a twist that surprises you (braised pork belly with jicama and lime or watermelon with arugula, walnuts and bleu cheese).

The best way to describe Bouchee is to say it's on the order of Willy Wonka's chocolate factory only stuff made of dough and chopping knives and stirring ladles. Once I was there about 11 a..m. when they'd posted a sign saying something like, "We are all out of pastries. Thanks to all the hungry mouths who presented us with this high-class dilemma."

data.title: Excellent food, tight quarters
data.text: Some friends and I met here for lunch. It's conveniently located on the Fayetteville square. The pastries on display look luscious. Everything we ordered was wonderful. I would definitely go again, but in peak times I would take my order to eat on the square or at home. The space is tiny. Some of the tables are high with backless stools. They're not very comfortable and even less so when a large person sits behind you! The man who sat behind me was just a big guy, but he kept bumping me. I hope they're able to expand into a larger space.

data.title: French in NWArkansas
data.text: I've been going here since they started serving their delicacies from a food truck and have yet to be disappointed. It's a cute gem located on the Fayetteville square. My favorites are the croissants, cinnamon rolls (they're huge!) and their sandwiches. They also make macarons, but they go fairly quickly.  If you're visiting the farmers market on Saturdays, best to visit them first to grab macarons if that's on your shopping list :). Glad to have this bakery/cafe in NWA.

data.title: They have wonderful treats to tempt you
data.text: I met a friend here for breakfast one Saturday morning.   We had a salted caramel chocolate tart.  It was delicious.  I have also had their chocolate corks.  They too are delicious.  They have French pressed coffee.

data.title: Good food
data.text: Went to Bouchee for breakfast and ended up having the eggs benedict with smoked salmon.  It was very good, but came with a salad which was rather bizarre for breakfast.  Nice little place, but they could use more staff as apparently there was only one man working who took orders and also prepared them!  I did think it was rather pricey for what we got.  But, I'd like to see what happens after they have some time to work things out.

data.title: Intimate and delicious
data.text: Saw a review of this little café in a magazine in our hotel room.  We planned on eating brunch there on Saturday morning, but we didn't arrive until noon.  The cinnamon rolls were gone.  That was our main reason for going.  But, we stayed anyway and ordered French onion soup, Kale quiche, ham and cheese croissant, and a ham sandwich with a fried egg on top.  I don't remember what it was called.  Everything was delicious.  The bread on the sandwich was toasted and buttery and warm. The cheese on the soup was creamy, stringy and had little burn marks - perfect!  The broth was hot and there were lots of onions in the bowl.  The kale quiche was also very, very good.  Brown on the top, but soft, eggy, creamy inside.  The quiche and the sandwich came with a small salad that was also very good.  The café is very small and has tiny tables.
